#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:2
msgid "Advanced Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:8
msgid "Customizing Pool Behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:10
msgid ""
"The :class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager` class automatically handles creating :"
"class:`~connectionpool.ConnectionPool` instances for each host as needed. By "
"default, it will keep a maximum of 10 :class:`~connectionpool."
"ConnectionPool` instances. If you're making requests to many different hosts "
"it might improve performance to increase this number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:16
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(num_pools=50)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:22
msgid ""
"However, keep in mind that this does increase memory and socket consumption."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:24
msgid ""
"Similarly, the :class:`~connectionpool.ConnectionPool` class keeps a pool of "
"individual :class:`~connection.HTTPConnection` instances. These connections "
"are used during an individual request and returned to the pool when the "
"request is complete. By default only one connection will be saved for re-"
"use. If you are making many requests to the same host simultaneously it "
"might improve performance to increase this number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:31
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(maxsize=10)\n"
"# Alternatively\n"
"pool = urllib3.HTTPConnectionPool(\"google.com\", maxsize=10)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:39
msgid ""
"The behavior of the pooling for :class:`~connectionpool.ConnectionPool` is "
"different from :class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager`. By default, if a new "
"request is made and there is no free connection in the pool then a new "
"connection will be created. However, this connection will not be saved if "
"more than ``maxsize`` connections exist. This means that ``maxsize`` does "
"not determine the maximum number of connections that can be open to a "
"particular host, just the maximum number of connections to keep in the pool. "
"However, if you specify ``block=True`` then there can be at most ``maxsize`` "
"connections open to a particular host."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:48
msgid ""
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(maxsize=10, block=True)\n"
"\n"
"# Alternatively\n"
"pool = urllib3.HTTPConnectionPool(\"google.com\", maxsize=10, block=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:55
msgid ""
"Any new requests will block until a connection is available from the pool. "
"This is a great way to prevent flooding a host with too many connections in "
"multi-threaded applications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:63
msgid "Streaming and I/O"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:65
msgid ""
"When using ``preload_content=True`` (the default setting) the response body "
"will be read immediately into memory and the HTTP connection will be "
"released back into the pool without manual intervention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:69
msgid ""
"However, when dealing with responses of large or unknown length, it's often "
"better to stream the response content using ``preload_content=False``. "
"Setting ``preload_content`` to ``False`` means that urllib3 will only read "
"from the socket when data is requested."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:74
msgid ""
"When using ``preload_content=False``, you need to manually release the HTTP "
"connection back to the connection pool so that it can be re-used. To ensure "
"the HTTP connection is in a valid state before being re-used all data should "
"be read off the wire."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:79
msgid ""
"You can call the  :meth:`~response.HTTPResponse.drain_conn` to throw away "
"unread data still on the wire. This call isn't necessary if data has already "
"been completely read from the response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:83
msgid ""
"After all data is read you can call :meth:`~response.HTTPResponse."
"release_conn` to release the connection into the pool."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:86
msgid ""
"You can call the :meth:`~response.HTTPResponse.close` to close the "
"connection, but this call doesn’t return the connection to the pool, throws "
"away the unread data on the wire, and leaves the connection in an undefined "
"protocol state. This is desirable if you prefer not reading data from the "
"socket to re-using the HTTP connection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:92
msgid ""
":meth:`~response.HTTPResponse.stream` lets you iterate over chunks of the "
"response content."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:94
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"resp = urllib3.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"https://httpbin.org/bytes/1024\",\n"
"    preload_content=False\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"for chunk in resp.stream(32):\n"
"    print(chunk)\n"
"    # b\"\\x9e\\xa97'\\x8e\\x1eT ....\n"
"\n"
"resp.release_conn()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:110
msgid ""
"However, you can also treat the :class:`~response.HTTPResponse` instance as "
"a file-like object. This allows you to do buffering:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:113
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"resp = urllib3.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"https://httpbin.org/bytes/1024\",\n"
"    preload_content=False\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"print(resp.read(4))\n"
"# b\"\\x88\\x1f\\x8b\\xe5\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:126
msgid ""
"Calls to :meth:`~response.HTTPResponse.read()` will block until more "
"response data is available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:129
msgid ""
"import io\n"
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"resp = urllib3.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"https://httpbin.org/bytes/1024\",\n"
"    preload_content=False\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"reader = io.BufferedReader(resp, 8)\n"
"print(reader.read(4))\n"
"# b\"\\xbf\\x9c\\xd6\"\n"
"\n"
"resp.release_conn()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:146
msgid ""
"You can use this file-like object to do things like decode the content "
"using :mod:`codecs`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:149
msgid ""
"import codecs\n"
"import json\n"
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"reader = codecs.getreader(\"utf-8\")\n"
"\n"
"resp = urllib3.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"https://httpbin.org/ip\",\n"
"    preload_content=False\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"print(json.load(reader(resp)))\n"
"# {\"origin\": \"127.0.0.1\"}\n"
"\n"
"resp.release_conn()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:171
msgid "Proxies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:173
msgid ""
"You can use :class:`~poolmanager.ProxyManager` to tunnel requests through an "
"HTTP proxy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:176
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"proxy = urllib3.ProxyManager(\"https://localhost:3128/\")\n"
"proxy.request(\"GET\", \"https://google.com/\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:183
msgid ""
"The usage of :class:`~poolmanager.ProxyManager` is the same as :class:"
"`~poolmanager.PoolManager`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:186
msgid ""
"You can connect to a proxy using HTTP, HTTPS or SOCKS. urllib3's behavior "
"will be different depending on the type of proxy you selected and the "
"destination you're contacting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:191
msgid "HTTP and HTTPS Proxies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:193
msgid ""
"Both HTTP/HTTPS proxies support HTTP and HTTPS destinations. The only "
"difference between them is if you need to establish a TLS connection to the "
"proxy first. You can specify which proxy you need to contact by specifying "
"the proper proxy scheme. (i.e ``http://`` or ``https://``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:198
msgid ""
"urllib3's behavior will be different depending on your proxy and destination:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:200
msgid "HTTP proxy + HTTP destination"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:201
msgid ""
"Your request will be forwarded with the `absolute URI <https://datatracker."
"ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9112#name-absolute-form>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:204
msgid "HTTP proxy + HTTPS destination"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:205
msgid ""
"A TCP tunnel will be established with a `HTTP CONNECT <https://datatracker."
"ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9110#name-connect>`_. Afterward a TLS connection will "
"be established with the destination and your request will be sent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:210
msgid "HTTPS proxy + HTTP destination"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:211
msgid ""
"A TLS connection will be established to the proxy and later your request "
"will be forwarded with the `absolute URI <https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/"
"html/rfc9112#name-absolute-form>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:215
msgid "HTTPS proxy + HTTPS destination"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:216
msgid ""
"A TLS-in-TLS tunnel will be established.  An initial TLS connection will be "
"established to the proxy, then an `HTTP CONNECT <https://datatracker.ietf."
"org/doc/html/rfc9110#name-connect>`_ will be sent to establish a TCP "
"connection to the destination and finally a second TLS connection will be "
"established to the destination. You can customize the :class:`ssl."
"SSLContext` used for the proxy TLS connection through the "
"``proxy_ssl_context`` argument of the :class:`~poolmanager.ProxyManager` "
"class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:225
msgid ""
"For HTTPS proxies we also support forwarding your requests to HTTPS "
"destinations with an `absolute URI <https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/"
"rfc9112#name-absolute-form>`_ if the ``use_forwarding_for_https`` argument "
"is set to ``True``. We strongly recommend you **only use this option with "
"trusted or corporate proxies** as the proxy will have full visibility of "
"your requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:234
msgid "Your proxy appears to only use HTTP and not HTTPS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:236
msgid ""
"If you're receiving the :class:`~urllib3.exceptions.ProxyError` and it "
"mentions your proxy only speaks HTTP and not HTTPS here's what to do to "
"solve your issue:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:239
msgid ""
"If you're using ``urllib3`` directly, make sure the URL you're passing into :"
"class:`urllib3.ProxyManager` starts with ``http://`` instead of ``https://``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:242
msgid ""
"# Do this:\n"
"http = urllib3.ProxyManager(\"http://...\")\n"
"\n"
"# Not this:\n"
"http = urllib3.ProxyManager(\"https://...\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:250
msgid ""
"If instead you're using ``urllib3`` through another library like Requests "
"there are multiple ways your proxy could be mis-configured. You need to "
"figure out where the configuration isn't correct and make the fix there. "
"Some common places to look are environment variables like ``HTTP_PROXY``, "
"``HTTPS_PROXY``, and ``ALL_PROXY``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:255
msgid ""
"Ensure that the values for all of these environment variables starts with "
"``http://`` and not ``https://``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:258
msgid ""
"# Check your existing environment variables in bash\n"
"$ env | grep \"_PROXY\"\n"
"HTTP_PROXY=http://127.0.0.1:8888\n"
"HTTPS_PROXY=https://127.0.0.1:8888  # <--- This setting is the problem!\n"
"\n"
"# Make the fix in your current session and test your script\n"
"$ export HTTPS_PROXY=\"http://127.0.0.1:8888\"\n"
"$ python test-proxy.py  # This should now pass.\n"
"\n"
"# Persist your change in your shell 'profile' (~/.bashrc, ~/.profile, ~/."
"bash_profile, etc)\n"
"# You may need to logout and log back in to ensure this works across all "
"programs.\n"
"$ vim ~/.bashrc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:273
msgid ""
"If you're on Windows or macOS your proxy may be getting set at a system "
"level. To check this first ensure that the above environment variables "
"aren't set then run the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:277
msgid "$ python -c 'import urllib.request; print(urllib.request.getproxies())'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:281
msgid "If the output of the above command isn't empty and looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:283
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  \"http\": \"http://127.0.0.1:8888\",\n"
"  \"https\": \"https://127.0.0.1:8888\"  # <--- This setting is the "
"problem!\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:290
msgid ""
"Search how to configure proxies on your operating system and change the "
"``https://...`` URL into ``http://``. After you make the change the return "
"value of ``urllib.request.getproxies()`` should be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:293
msgid ""
"{  # Everything is good here! :)\n"
"  \"http\": \"http://127.0.0.1:8888\",\n"
"  \"https\": \"http://127.0.0.1:8888\"\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:300
msgid ""
"If you still can't figure out how to configure your proxy after all these "
"steps please `join our community Discord <https://discord.gg/urllib3>`_ and "
"we'll try to help you with your issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:304
msgid "SOCKS Proxies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:307
msgid ""
"For SOCKS, you can use :class:`~contrib.socks.SOCKSProxyManager` to connect "
"to SOCKS4 or SOCKS5 proxies. In order to use SOCKS proxies you will need to "
"install `PySocks <https://pypi.org/project/PySocks/>`_ or install urllib3 "
"with the ``socks`` extra:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:312
msgid "python -m pip install urllib3[socks]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:316
msgid ""
"Once PySocks is installed, you can use :class:`~contrib.socks."
"SOCKSProxyManager`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:319
msgid ""
"from urllib3.contrib.socks import SOCKSProxyManager\n"
"\n"
"proxy = SOCKSProxyManager(\"socks5h://localhost:8889/\")\n"
"proxy.request(\"GET\", \"https://google.com/\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:327
msgid ""
"It is recommended to use ``socks5h://`` or ``socks4a://`` schemes in your "
"``proxy_url`` to ensure that DNS resolution is done from the remote server "
"instead of client-side when connecting to a domain name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:335
msgid "Custom TLS Certificates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:337
msgid ""
"Instead of using `certifi <https://certifi.io/>`_ you can provide your own "
"certificate authority bundle. This is useful for cases where you've "
"generated your own certificates or when you're using a private certificate "
"authority. Just provide the full path to the certificate bundle when "
"creating a :class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:343
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"    cert_reqs=\"CERT_REQUIRED\",\n"
"    ca_certs=\"/path/to/your/certificate_bundle\"\n"
")\n"
"resp = http.request(\"GET\", \"https://example.com\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:353
msgid ""
"When you specify your own certificate bundle only requests that can be "
"verified with that bundle will succeed. It's recommended to use a separate :"
"class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager` to make requests to URLs that do not need "
"the custom certificate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:361
msgid "Custom SNI Hostname"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:363
msgid ""
"If you want to create a connection to a host over HTTPS which uses SNI, "
"there are two places where the hostname is expected. It must be included in "
"the Host header sent, so that the server will know which host is being "
"requested. The hostname should also match the certificate served by the "
"server, which is checked by urllib3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:369
msgid ""
"Normally, urllib3 takes care of setting and checking these values for you "
"when you connect to a host by name. However, it's sometimes useful to set a "
"connection's expected Host header and certificate hostname (subject), "
"especially when you are connecting without using name resolution. For "
"example, you could connect to a server by IP using HTTPS like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:375
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"pool = urllib3.HTTPSConnectionPool(\n"
"    \"104.154.89.105\",\n"
"    server_hostname=\"badssl.com\"\n"
")\n"
"pool.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"/\",\n"
"    headers={\"Host\": \"badssl.com\"},\n"
"    assert_same_host=False\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:391
msgid ""
"Note that when you use a connection in this way, you must specify "
"``assert_same_host=False``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:394
msgid ""
"This is useful when DNS resolution for ``example.org`` does not match the "
"address that you would like to use. The IP may be for a private interface, "
"or you may want to use a specific host under round-robin DNS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:402
msgid "Verifying TLS against a different host"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:404
msgid ""
"If the server you're connecting to presents a different certificate than the "
"hostname or the SNI hostname, you can use ``assert_hostname``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:407
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"pool = urllib3.HTTPSConnectionPool(\n"
"    \"wrong.host.badssl.com\",\n"
"    assert_hostname=\"badssl.com\",\n"
")\n"
"pool.request(\"GET\", \"/\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:421
msgid "Client Certificates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:423
msgid ""
"You can also specify a client certificate. This is useful when both the "
"server and the client need to verify each other's identity. Typically these "
"certificates are issued from the same authority. To use a client "
"certificate, provide the full path when creating a :class:`~poolmanager."
"PoolManager`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:428
msgid ""
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"    cert_file=\"/path/to/your/client_cert.pem\",\n"
"    cert_reqs=\"CERT_REQUIRED\",\n"
"    ca_certs=\"/path/to/your/certificate_bundle\"\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:436
msgid ""
"If you have an encrypted client certificate private key you can use the "
"``key_password`` parameter to specify a password to decrypt the key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:439
msgid ""
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"    cert_file=\"/path/to/your/client_cert.pem\",\n"
"    cert_reqs=\"CERT_REQUIRED\",\n"
"    key_file=\"/path/to/your/client.key\",\n"
"    key_password=\"keyfile_password\"\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:448
msgid ""
"If your key isn't encrypted the ``key_password`` parameter isn't required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:451
msgid "TLS minimum and maximum versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:453
msgid ""
"When the configured TLS versions by urllib3 aren't compatible with the TLS "
"versions that the server is willing to use you'll likely see an error like "
"this one:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:456
msgid ""
"SSLError(1, '[SSL: UNSUPPORTED_PROTOCOL] unsupported protocol (_ssl.c:1124)')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:460
msgid ""
"Starting in v2.0 by default urllib3 uses TLS 1.2 and later so servers that "
"only support TLS 1.1 or earlier will not work by default with urllib3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:463
msgid ""
"To fix the issue you'll need to use the ``ssl_minimum_version`` option along "
"with the `TLSVersion enum`_ in the standard library ``ssl`` module to "
"configure urllib3 to accept a wider range of TLS versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:466
msgid ""
"For the best security it's a good idea to set this value to the version of "
"TLS that's being used by the server. For example if the server requires TLS "
"1.0 you'd configure urllib3 like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:469
msgid ""
"import ssl\n"
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"    ssl_minimum_version=ssl.TLSVersion.TLSv1\n"
")\n"
"# This request works!\n"
"resp = http.request(\"GET\", \"https://tls-v1-0.badssl.com:1010\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:486
msgid "Certificate Validation and macOS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:488
msgid ""
"Apple-provided Python and OpenSSL libraries contain a patches that make them "
"automatically check the system keychain's certificates. This can be "
"surprising if you specify custom certificates and see requests unexpectedly "
"succeed. For example, if you are specifying your own certificate for "
"validation and the server presents a different certificate you would expect "
"the connection to fail. However, if that server presents a certificate that "
"is in the system keychain then the connection will succeed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:496
msgid ""
"`This article <https://hynek.me/articles/apple-openssl-verification-"
"surprises/>`_ has more in-depth analysis and explanation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:502
msgid "TLS Warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:504
msgid ""
"urllib3 will issue several different warnings based on the level of "
"certificate verification support. These warnings indicate particular "
"situations and can be resolved in different ways."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:508
msgid ":class:`~exceptions.InsecureRequestWarning`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:509
msgid ""
"This happens when a request is made to an HTTPS URL without certificate "
"verification enabled. Follow the :ref:`certificate verification <ssl>` guide "
"to resolve this warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:515
msgid ""
"Making unverified HTTPS requests is **strongly** discouraged, however, if "
"you understand the risks and wish to disable these warnings, you can use :"
"func:`~urllib3.disable_warnings`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:518
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"urllib3.disable_warnings()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:524
msgid ""
"Alternatively you can capture the warnings with the standard :mod:`logging` "
"module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:526
msgid "logging.captureWarnings(True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:530
msgid ""
"Finally, you can suppress the warnings at the interpreter level by setting "
"the ``PYTHONWARNINGS`` environment variable or by using the `-W flag "
"<https://docs.python.org/3/using/cmdline.html#cmdoption-w>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:535
msgid "Brotli Encoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:537
msgid ""
"Brotli is a compression algorithm created by Google with better compression "
"than gzip and deflate and is supported by urllib3 if the `Brotli <https://"
"pypi.org/Brotli>`_ package or `brotlicffi <https://github.com/python-hyper/"
"brotlicffi>`_ package is installed. You may also request the package be "
"installed via the ``urllib3[brotli]`` extra:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:543
msgid "$ python -m pip install urllib3[brotli]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:547
msgid ""
"Here's an example using brotli encoding via the ``Accept-Encoding`` header:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:549
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"urllib3.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"https://www.google.com/\",\n"
"    headers={\"Accept-Encoding\": \"br\"}\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:560
msgid "Zstandard Encoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:562
msgid ""
"`Zstandard <https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8878>`_ is a "
"compression algorithm created by Facebook with better compression than "
"brotli, gzip and deflate (see `benchmarks <https://facebook.github.io/zstd/"
"#benchmarks>`_) and is supported by urllib3 in Python 3.14+ using the "
"`compression.zstd <https://peps.python.org/pep-0784/>`_ standard library "
"module and for Python 3.13 and earlier if the `backports.zstd package "
"<https://pypi.org/project/backports.zstd/>`_ is installed. You may also "
"request the package be installed via the ``urllib3[zstd]`` extra:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:569
msgid ""
"# This is only necessary on Python 3.13 and earlier.\n"
"# Otherwise zstandard support is included in the Python standard library.\n"
"$ python -m pip install urllib3[zstd]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:577
msgid ""
"Zstandard support in urllib3 requires using v0.18.0 or later of the "
"``zstandard`` package. If the version installed is less than v0.18.0 then "
"Zstandard support won't be enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:580
msgid ""
"Here's an example using zstd encoding via the ``Accept-Encoding`` header:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:582
msgid ""
"import urllib3\n"
"\n"
"urllib3.request(\n"
"    \"GET\",\n"
"    \"https://www.facebook.com/\",\n"
"    headers={\"Accept-Encoding\": \"zstd\"}\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:594
msgid "Decrypting Captured TLS Sessions with Wireshark"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:595
msgid ""
"Python supports logging of TLS pre-master secrets. With these secrets tools "
"like `Wireshark <https://wireshark.org>`_ can decrypt captured network "
"traffic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:599
msgid "To enable this simply define environment variable `SSLKEYLOGFILE`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:601
msgid "export SSLKEYLOGFILE=/path/to/keylogfile.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:605
msgid ""
"Then configure the key logfile in `Wireshark <https://wireshark.org>`_, see "
"`Wireshark TLS Decryption <https://wiki.wireshark.org/TLS#TLS_Decryption>`_ "
"for instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:609
msgid "Custom SSL Contexts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:611
msgid ""
"You can exercise fine-grained control over the urllib3 SSL configuration by "
"providing a :class:`ssl.SSLContext <python:ssl.SSLContext>` object. For "
"purposes of compatibility, we recommend you obtain one from :func:`~urllib3."
"util.create_urllib3_context`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:616
msgid ""
"Once you have a context object, you can mutate it to achieve whatever effect "
"you'd like. For example, the code below loads the default SSL certificates, "
"sets the :data:`ssl.OP_ENABLE_MIDDLEBOX_COMPAT<python:ssl."
"OP_ENABLE_MIDDLEBOX_COMPAT>` flag that isn't set by default, and then makes "
"a HTTPS request:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:621
msgid ""
"import ssl\n"
"\n"
"from urllib3 import PoolManager\n"
"from urllib3.util import create_urllib3_context\n"
"\n"
"ctx = create_urllib3_context()\n"
"ctx.load_default_certs()\n"
"ctx.options |= ssl.OP_ENABLE_MIDDLEBOX_COMPAT\n"
"\n"
"with PoolManager(ssl_context=ctx) as pool:\n"
"    pool.request(\"GET\", \"https://www.google.com/\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced-usage.rst:635
msgid ""
"Note that this is different from passing an ``options`` argument to :func:"
"`~urllib3.util.create_urllib3_context` because we don't overwrite the "
"default options: we only add a new one."
msgstr ""
